{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491024","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491024"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:28:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:28:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"806"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"806","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/806"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.19,0.57,0.01,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"806"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111027"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"806","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/806"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"806"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93144"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"536"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"923"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1051"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6928"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7167"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8093"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8167"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42152"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45108"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111027","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111027"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman is brought into the Emergency Department (ED) after a motor vehicle crash. She is able to recall the events and was driving across an intersection when her vehicle was hit on the driver\u0027s side by a car running the red light. The car door was pushed in and she now has severe pain in the right side of her chest and this makes breathing difficult. While with the ambulance a right sided needle thoracocentesis was performed with minimal air aspirated. On examination in the ED her blood pressure is 134/86 mmHg and pulse 92/min. As the examination proceeds the patient work of breathing increases with her breaths becoming increasingly shallow. She has a midline trachea with reduced breath sounds are on the right side with an obvious deformity on the right exhibiting chest recession on inspiration. Her current oxygen saturations are 95% on 15L of oxygen via non-rebreather. A chest X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Non-invasive positive pressure ventilation","Endotracheal intubation and positive pressure ventilation","Intercostal chest drain","Tracheostomy","Emergency room thoracotomy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a \u003Cstrong\u003Eflail segment\u003C/strong\u003E with \u003Cstrong\u003Ehydropneumothorax\u003C/strong\u003E causing increased work of breathing. The patient is able to maintain adequate oxygenation at this stage but is still requiring maximum supplemental oxygen therapy as the majority of the lung is collapsed. \u003Cstrong\u003EAn intercostal chest drain or thoracostomy\u003C/strong\u003E is required to ensure that she does not progress to respiratory failure. The chest drain placement will allow for the ongoing removal of blood or air due to the underlying trauma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWith \u003Cstrong\u003Eflail chest\u003C/strong\u003E, the detached segment of the\u003Cstrong\u003E chest wall is pulled into the chest cavity during inspiration\u003C/strong\u003E and pushed outward during expiration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eparadoxical chest movement (\u003C/strong\u003Ereduced effectiveness of ventilation),\u003Cstrong\u003E severe pain, \u003C/strong\u003Eassociated\u003Cstrong\u003E lung contusions, chest wall haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E, and other \u003Cstrong\u003Econcurrent trauma\u003C/strong\u003E contribute to the increased work of breathing and impending respiratory failure and other complications (e.g., pneumonia, atelectasis, etc.).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-invasive positive pressure ventilation or endotracheal intubation with positive pressure ventilation \u003C/strong\u003Eare often needed as part of pulmonary support to the patient with flail chest. However, they are reserved after \u003Cstrong\u003Eaggressive pulmonary toilet\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eadequate pain control,\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Echest physiotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-invasive positive pressure ventilation \u003C/strong\u003Edelivers positive pressure to patients through nasal, facial, or helmet interfaces without an endotracheal airway and should be used in cooperative patients without hemodynamic instability, facial injuries, or a risk of aspiration. Pneumothorax may get aggravated when positive pressure (CPAP) is used if there is also an element of tension pneumothorax, even with the trachea remaining midline, so it should be used cautiously.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndotracheal intubation and positive pressure ventilation \u003C/strong\u003Emay be required if the interventions of needle decompression and chest drainage are insufficient to address the underlying hypoxia and respiratory failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETracheostomy\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered in the future if \u003Cstrong\u003Elong-term ventilation\u003C/strong\u003E is required, which is possible for this condition, but this would not be first-line management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn\u003Cstrong\u003E emergency room thoracotomy \u003C/strong\u003Eis performed in selected cases of direct thoracic injury concurrently with ACLS/ATLS resuscitation, but it should not be performed on any patient who continues to have vital signs, including detectable but hypotensive blood pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther key parts of management include an aggressive analgesic regimen, as rib fractures are a very painful condition. The use of intercostal nerve blocks, which spare the need for systemic analgesia with its attendant side effects, is particularly effective. If the patient fails to improve with invasive ventilation, there should be a consultation with cardiothoracic surgery for possible surgical fixation of the ribs to achieve chest wall stabilisation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Conservative management of rib fractures initially involves thoracostomy drainage for pneumothorax/hemothorax (when present), limiting fluid during trauma resuscitation to reduce edema in contused lung, and appropriate prophylactic therapies.","The paradoxical chest movement, severe pain, associated lung contusion and other trauma contribute to the increased work of breathing and impending respiratory failure","Management of a flail chest should include these areas of concern; maintaining adequate ventilation, fluid and pain management, and management of the unstable chest wall."],"references":["Pettiford BL, Luketich JD, Landreneau RJ. The Management of Flail Chest. Thorac Surg Clin. 2007 Feb; 17(1): 25-33.","Perera TB, King KC. Flail Chest. Statpearls. 2020 November 21.","Chapman BC, Herbert B, Rodil M, et al. RibScore: A novel radiographic score based on fracture pattern that predicts pneumonia, respiratory failure, and tracheostomy. J Trauma Acute Care Surg 2016; 80:95.","https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3132366/","https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534090/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93144"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"806"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19224"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19224","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19224"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/fd8a67cf-e667-4ffc-a481-ab4e9996098a.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/fd8a67cf-e667-4ffc-a481-ab4e9996098a.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":440,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93144","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93144"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-07T08:22:12+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-07T08:22:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"806"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111027"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":